</span></p></div></div></div><div class="sc-faUpoM jULbDz pf-121_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fydGpi bMfPUC pf-122_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-edERGn cHFtyQ pf-123_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-125_">Leave the clutter out of your bedroom.</span></h3><p class="sc-iukxot iZqxsD pf-126_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-128_">A clean and tidy environment increases the quality of sleep and allows you to create the perfect atmosphere to promote relaxation.&nbsp;</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-edERGn cHFtyQ pf-129_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-131_">Create a positive environment.&nbsp;</span></h3><p class="sc-iukxot iZqxsD pf-132_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-134_">For example, envelop yourself in a quiet and peaceful room. Silence allows us not only to fall asleep easily but also to dream better.<br><br>Of course, there may be different degrees of sensitivity to noise. Some people, despite the background noise, sleep without problems, while others need absolute silence to do it. The latter usually have a very sensitive perception, waking up to the slightest noise.<br><br>What is indisputable however is that, regardless of the degree of sensitivity we have, the ideal is to sleep in a pleasant environment with nothing that can disturb it.</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-edERGn cHFtyQ pf-135_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-137_">Avoid the screens.&nbsp;</span></h3><p class="sc-iukxot iZqxsD pf-138_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-hgKiOD hnskCB pf-140_">As is well known, the light of the screens causes sleep disturbances.<br><br>The main problem can be attributed to the light it gives off. It is scientifically proven tha